TRIP COMMENTS: I went on a hike with Glenn Anderson.  This was the first time I ever saw a colony of p martins nesting in old snags.  I had only seen them before nesting under bridges in holes.  The NRW Swallows were also doing something peculiar.  They were sunning themselves on the metal roof of a barn flying back and forth to the wires where all the cliff swallows were gathered, but it was all NRW on the hot metal roof.  I went back 3Xs in Aug 2011 and realized it was the Cadre Pt Loop Trail.

Yellow-bellied Sapsucker: Red crown and throat completely outlined in black.  White supercilium wrapped around back of head - no red on nape.  Black eyeline connected to lateral crown stripe at bill.  White line extending from base of maxilla back between black eyeline and malar.  Mantle black with extensive white barring.  White rump patch.  Black line extends up center of white nape to white line below crown.  Scapulars and outer wing coverts black.  Inner greater and median wing coverts white creating a white wing patch.  Primaries and secondaries black with white barring.  Tertials black with white scallops and other internal markings.  Underparts dingy white with thin dark gray barring - no yellow visible on belly.  Undertail coverts white with black central streaks.  Visible rectrices were black (some white visible) and pointed.  Bird was foraging in sapsucker wells on pine.

Did a 10 minute point count at entrance gate near Friant Rd and then added birds as I went. Drove to entrance station and walked for 1 hour near river. Drove to campground. Walked around upstream for 75 minutes. Drove to ponds at downstream end of park and stayed for 15 minutes.

LOCALITY: IRWD San Joaquin Marsh & Wildlife Sanctuary, Irvine

TRIP COMMENTS: Leo Ohtsuki and I birded the east side until 0830. It seemed very quiet, but a nice marine layer is present (though it may have moved in later last night than previous nights – also this morning was probably the first since Friday, May 2, that I did not hear SWTH calling overhead at my house before sunrise), so we were thinking where are the birds? At this point we had decent numbers of some migrants (SWTH – 10; WIWA – 15), but very poor numbers for other “common” migrants (WAVI – 4; YEWA – 4; TOWA – 2). We went to the west side and found the migrants. They seemed to be scattered throughout the west side, but in particular, there were unusually large numbers in the “sterile” pine trees next to the ruderal field that is the future Senior Citizen housing site. Leo and I then decided to return to the east side to see if migrants were "filtering" into the park. We ran into Dick and Pat Cabe and Jim Pike and there were perhaps more birds, but it still seemed relatively quiet on the east side. Strange. Leo and I called it a day at 1100 (he was going home for lunch – Yasuko had craving for a hamburger) and I was going home to watch the Lakers at 1230.

TRIP COMMENTS: Weather: mostly sunny, breezy, ~63-66 degrees. Hazy.----I biked to Upper Newport Bay on 11/29. I rode around on Bayview Drive on the way to Little Corona City Beach in the morning and on the way home in the afternoon. In the morning the tide was high but receding, and on the way back it was low enough to form extensive mudflats. Lots of birds were present.

On 11/15/08 there was a very high tide (6.9 feet) scheduled around 9:30 a.m. I rode my bike to Upper Newport Bay to look for birds flushed out of the marsh by the tide. I arrived at the boardwalk near the nature center shortly after eight and hung around until after ten thirty. As the marsh flooded, birds began appearing - lots of rails, bitterns, and even a Short-eared Owl. The owl was very cooperative, flying around and sitting in the open for extended periods of time. ----Many other birders were there with me, including Robert McNab, Steve Sosensky, Bruce Aird, Tom Miko, and others. ----Weather: very hot (80''s, low 90''s), very windy (gusts ~15-20 mph), sunny, and extremely dry.

Weather: sunny, breezy, warm. ----I biked to UNB, birding it on the way to the beach in mid-morning and again on the way home in the early afternoon. There were thousands of birds, and I didn''t even try to estimate numbers for some species because of the two trips and the sheer number of birds spead over the bay. LOSH was a new Bigby bird. ----The two CLRA were also great (best look I''ve had), along with the EUWI.

The Scarlet Tanager was a young male, found in the riparian area below the dam. a medium sized passerine, larger than the Yellow-rumped Warblers in the same tree. Underparts were yellow , similar to Western Tanger. The wings were jet black with no wingbars. the back was green as was the head. the tail was black. The bill was a pale yellow/horn color. It did not vocalize. It disapeared into the thicket before anyone else could see it. Curtiz Marantz found the Northern Waterthrush . Two good park birds in one day, the tanager was also a county bird. The other birders included Curtis Marantz, Chet McGaugh, Mike San Miguel,Vernon and Andrew Howe, Tom Wurster and Bill Deppe

The male Rose-breasted Grosbeak sang beautifully for a long time from a wire, and then the top of a willow, while a small group of us, drawn out by the report on the SD Birds website, listened. A harrier relentlessly pursued a bird back and forth across the sky -- we disagreed what the bird was, but it was definitely racing for its life, and most of the time the harrier was only a few feet behind. At one point the bird increased its distance ahead of the harrier, and then a second harrier appeared and drove the bird back closer to the first one again. They got too far up the canyon for us to tell what happened.--Also, Pacific Slope Flycatchers seemed to have a nest on a treetrunk by the stream, where high water earlier in the year had wrapped alot of reeds & debris around the trunk creating a sheltered spot. Altogether an exciting birding day.

TRIP COMMENTS: A woman was feeding lettuce to the domestic graylag geese and canada geese.  She told me that she had earlier observed this flock of geese being aggressive towards the two swan geese, "kicking them out" so to speak, which is why she thinks they are always found in a different area. I did notice, however, that one of the graylag geese had a mild knob on its bill suggesting it might have been the result of a hybrid with the swan goose.  Who knows?  There''s no way for me to enter swan/graylag goose hybrids in ebird, however.

TRIP COMMENTS: I thought I saw a Say''s phoebe too...not sure, however.  Also, we both saw a sparrow that we couldn''t ID.  It very clearly had a notched tail (rather than the rounded ones on song sparrows).  It was dark on the back and had some gray on the side of the head.  All the song sparrows in the area were very dark.

Probably saw the stint but didn''t know it. I ran away when the flocks started flying in so the count is very undercounted for terns, sandpipers and plovers and all the other moving things. . . my binocs were not up to the task.

I saw the osprey catch a huge fish, very dramatically.  Two of the black skimmers were bickering with each other.  I spent nearly the whole time standing in a single spot, gradually identifying everything that I could.  The yellowlegs were not near anything else so I had no reference frame for size.  I also thought I saw a Forster''s tern or two, but they were very far off.  When I got back to the car, I saw the falcon.  It was just soaring, and nothing seemed particularly scared of it, a few of the peeps took flight when it flew over.

We also saw at least 3 of a sandpiper like bird that we are still trying to ID.  It had a very dark brown back, much darker than any of the nearby willets or godwits, and it had a short, slightly downcurved bill.
Gliderport to beach, a mile up and back each way.  ----Partly cloudy, wind L, 23C

LOCALITY: Lake Cachuma - narrows and east end
TRIP COMMENTS: With Holly Keefe. For the annual Lake Cachuma Bald Eagle count, occupied the narrows and the east end. We were left off on the south shore at the entrance to the narrows and walked about 300 meters east to an observation point for the east end. At least one of us occupied this location from 9:30 to 11:40. Sunny, calm. Cool early, warming later.

Birding with Zach Phillips and Tara Stewart. --Intent: This was the day of the Cachuma Eagle Inventory. We were one of 14 groups dropped at various spots around the lake and left to observe and document the presence of Osprey and eagles for 3 hours. We took additional notes on all species of birds seen; other groups did not do this. --Coverage: We saw no eagles but we had the time to do a careful inventory of the bay and surrounding upland. We stood consistently at 34.5786°N, 119.9294°W (NAD83/WGS84). From this point we could see nearly all of the bay. --Weather: upper 6os, slight breeze from the S, clear. Eleven inches of rain ------Image of Santa Cruz Bay on Jun 2009 from Google Earth.------Looking from our observation point to NE.

Estimate of actual party size. My notes don't say who was in the boat. This was the annual Lake Cachuma Bald Eagle count. Although I've noted the duration was 4 hrs, these observations pertain to only about an hour of that total. Three hours in the middle are covered under a checklist for the narrows and the east end, where Holly Keefe and I were stationed during that time. These totals are for birds seen from the boat in transit between the marina and our station, including birds seen during the trip out and the trip back.

LOCALITY: Watsonville Slough and Struve Slough confluence
TRIP COMMENTS: Thirteen participants joined us for any enjoyable morning of birding along Struve and Watsonville Sloughs. Highlights included displaying American Bitterns at Struve Slough, as well as large numbers of White Pelicans and Great Egrets. From the overlook on Watsonville Slough from Lee Road, several shorebirds were visible in the distance, but most were too far away to identify to species. An exception to this rule was a Long-billed Curlew that flew over then landed on the mudflats below. A total of 57 species (including Accipiter sp. and yellowlegs sp.) were recorded for the morning. Bernadette and Bob Ramer

Kayaked from Rumsey Bridge to Guinda Bridge.  --Singing YELLOW-BREASTED CHATS at 38.869111 N, 122.214583 W (east side of river), and --at 38.829478 W, 122.185903 W (west side of river, 200 yrds upstream of Guinda Bridge, easily accessible by car)(breeding has never been confirmed in Yolo County).  --Female adult PURPLE MARTIN at 38.847546 N, 122.196621 W on telephone wire over gravel bar, flew off WNW into tall cottonwoods; unprecedented for Capay Valley?  --SPOTTED SANDPIPERS at five scattered locations, two doing display flights.  Many species seen tending young (Killdeer, Cliff Swallow, etc.).    --Riparian habitat overrun by tamarisk and arundo virtually everywhere, both sides of river for the entire length.  --Ash-thr Flycatcher, Bewick''s Wren, Bullock''s Oriole much reduced from previous years.  However, Song Sparrow, House Wren, and Spotted Towhees much increased.
